	<tr>
		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row2"><span class="name"><a name="130889"></a><b>Dabrighter2</b></span><br /><span class="postdetails">Sage<br /><img src="images/gallery/Blade Runner/movie_blade_runner_howl.gif" alt="" border="0" /><br /><br />Joined: 03 Dec 2002<br />Posts: 760<br /></span><br /></td>
		<td class="row2" width="100%" height="28" valign="top"><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
				<td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=130889&amp;sid=edfe16336da78da8312f6375e663dd41#130889"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Wed Jan 28, 2004 10:13 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Re: /pet hold, /pet attack  VS   /pet back off, /pet attack</span></td>
			        <td valign="top" align="right" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="ignore.php?mode=add&amp;username=Dabrighter2&amp;topic=11150&amp;sid=edfe16336da78da8312f6375e663dd41"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_ignore.gif" alt="Add User to Ignore List" title="Add User to Ignore List" border="0" /></a> <a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=130889&amp;sid=edfe16336da78da8312f6375e663dd41"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Organica wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Scenario:  Group pulls one, /pet attack.  During the fight you get an add and want the pet to offtank.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Sequence 1:
<br />
1) /pet hold || backs the pet off the current target
<br />
2) target the add
<br />
3) /pet attack || the pet goes back to attacking the original target, not the add
<br />

<br />

<br />
Sequence 2:
<br />
1) /pet back off || backs the pet off the current target
<br />
2) target the add
<br />
3) /pet attack || the pet attacks the add as intended, all is well.
<br />

<br />

<br />
My Question:  Why does this happen, is this supposed to happen? Is there a way to clear the pets agro list or something, do i need to throw a /pet follow or something in there?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
First
<br />

<br />
/pet hold -- The pet ignores its hate list and returns "home"
<br />
/pet back off -- Clears the pets aggro list.
<br />
/pet attack  -- adds a very small amount of aggro to your target's aggro list.
<br />

<br />
In Sequence 1 the .
<br />
1) /pet hold  -- causes the pet to ignore its hate list and return "home"
<br />
the 
<br />
3) /pet attack -- cause your target to get a very small amount of aggro and breaks the hold command.  If the pet's original target has caused any damage to it, it has a lot more aggro than what the /pet attack gives.  Oonce the pet is told to attack, it starts attacking the mob on the top of its aggro list which will be the original mob.  
<br />

<br />
In Sequence 2 the 
<br />
1) /pet back off -- clears your pet's aggro list.  
<br />
the 
<br />
3) /pet attack -- adds a small amount aggro to your target and break the hold command.  The pet now attacks the mob which is the highest mob on the aggro list.  Since you just cleared it, it will be your target.  
<br />

<br />
The 
<br />
/pet back off
<br />
/pet attack 
<br />

<br />
is very effective at getting the pet to switch because at the instant the /pet attack is issued, your target is the highest thing on your pet's aggro list.  Keep in mind, if the original mob is still beating on your pet, if it successful hits it, it will move back to the top of your pets aggro list and the pet will switch back.  
<br />

<br />
To counter this, some people try putting /follow me or /pet hold in the macro to try and get the pet to move out of melee range before giving it an order to attack.  I don't really like this idea because the /follow me or the /pet hold just gives the mob more time to hit your pet and regain top aggro status before the it attacks the add.  I think it much more effective to reapply the /pet back off, /pet attack macro if he switches back to the original mob rather than try to add another macro command to get it to move. 
<br />

<br />
I use the /pet back off, /pet attack as my pet attack key.  If I want to stack mobs on the pets aggro list, I target the mob and use the pet attack button on the UI.  
<br />

<br />
Something else to note. 
<br />
About a year ago, they totally redid how macros are processed.  They introduced a lot of time dependencies that did not exist before. 
<br />

<br />
Example
<br />
/assist "Main Tank"
<br />
/pet attack
<br />
/cast 7
<br />

<br />
Before the Macro update, that macro would cause me to target the Main Tank's target, have my pet attack it, and then cast spell gem 7 on that target.  After the Macro update.  Half the time my pet would not attack and the pet would give me an invalid target.  What I determined was happing was most of the time the pet attack command was being processed before my target had changed and the pet truely did have an invalid target.
<br />

<br />
Because of this, I changed all of my macro's.  After every target change, I added a /1 Current target is %t.  {Chat channel 1 is my personal chat channel that no one else sees.  I use it for macro status messages}  I also suspected that if there were two /pet commands in a row, the second one would not be carried out, at least some of the time.  I went through all my macro's and made sure I did not have two /pet commands in sequence.  If nothing else, I added a /pause 1, in front of the first one.  This was a real pain to do because I have so many macros, but once I did it, my macros became stable again.  
<br />

<br />
My current pet attack macro is 
<br />
/pet back off
<br />
/1 %m is attacking %t
<br />
/pet attack
<br />

<br />
Putting that /1 %m is attacking %t in the macro really bothered me because I wanted the min amout of time to lapse between the /pet back off and /pet attack command.  But I have found this command to be very effective.  Additionally, have the chat line can show you that the reason you pet is not attacking is because you have yourself targeted, not that I have ever done that.  
<br />

<br />
Hope this helps<br />_________________<br />Dabrighter Blazemeister
<br />
