you can't queue multiple targets for your pet to attack. For that reason I recommend against it.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Good point.  
<br />

<br />
I view it this way.  
<br />
When I pust the pet attack macro from the keyboard, I want my pet to attack that mob.  Period.  No if, ands, buts.  This mob now.  
<br />

<br />
When I get an unwanted add, a mob on me, or a mob on a group member, I face the mob and push the Taget nearest NPC button.  Then I pust my pet attack macro until the pet starts attacking the mob and gets aggro.  Then, if I want to stack multiple mobs on my pets list, I just target them and use the pet attack command from the Pet UI window.  
<br />

<br />
Another option would be to have a second pet attack macro without the /pet back off.  
<br />

<br />
To me, stacking mobs on my pets aggro list is not often a pressue situation.  Getting my pet to aggro a add on me or a group member is.  A few seconds is the difference between living and dying in that situation.  I have setup my keyboards and commands to make this situation as easy to handle as possible.  
<br />

<br />
Again, you have a very valid point.  I understand wanting to stack mobs on your pet's aggro list and I have a method of doing that.<br />_________________<br />Dabrighter Blazemeister
