				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">If you make your pet attack key 
<br />
/pet back off 
<br />
/pet attack 
<br />
you can't queue multiple targets for your pet to attack. For that reason I recommend against it.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
While I see that as an argument against, the alternative of
<br />

<br />
key1: /pet hold; /pet back off
<br />
key2:/pet attack
<br />

<br />
Is terribly unreliable, becuase if the pet is aoed or attacked by anything while it's idle it will have strange and unpredictable aggro list behavior when you hit key2. Furthermore if the pet is engaged with a mob when you hit key one (to back it away) you almost surely will need to hit key1 again after the pet has fully disengaged before hitting key2.
<br />

<br />
Personally, I almost never have to queue an attack list, and queuing a list necessarily opens you up to having your pet attack strage targets since you can't reset his aggro list before sending him in. The few times I do I just use the pet-window's /pet attack button. I guess it all boils down to:
<br />

<br />
1. If you like to hit one key to disengage, and only one key to engage, and have the system be almost idiot prrof to attacking the wrong target, use my method.
<br />

<br />
2. If you really like to queue attacks at the exspense of having to hit two keys to engage the pet use the other method.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
